issue.body:
CPP.py defines raw strings as
multiline_string_delimiters = {'R("': ')"'}
That is incorrect.
See https://stackoverflow.com/questions/49416631/escape-r-in-a-raw-string-in-c
We currently can not describe balanced delimiters, so we can only provide one constant delimiter, so it should be
multiline_string_delimiters = {'R"(': '")'}

So passing this
{'E': RESULT_SEVERITY.MAJOR}
or this
{'e': RESULT_SEVERITY.MAJOR}
makes no difference.
difficulty/low so newcomers aren't confused about what this issue tries to achieve and this issue requires some reading on @linter ;)

comments.bodyText:
I implemented a slightly different approach to the problem. The original solution was to find the max_line_length setting from the source, increase the length of the max_line by 1 through a regex provided. But here there were two problems, one being the regex itself. It is hard to provide the regex for a language syntax (specially when the there are multiple max_lines) and the second being it is also difficult to generate the string from a regex and increase the line length by 1.
The alternative solution takes care of both of the above problems and also solves the issue. The solution is that we can get the max_line_length from the source and then decrease the max_line_length setting and run the bear, which will fail eventually.
@jayvdb Let me know if this is good enough :-)

